Always set a short `lock_timeout` before any DDL. If the migration cannot grab the lock in a few seconds, it aborts instead of holding a queue of waiters.

```sql
SET lock_timeout = '2s';
SET statement_timeout = '5min';
ALTER TABLE orders ADD COLUMN status text;
```

Without `lock_timeout`, your migration waits behind a slow query while every new query waits behind your migration. That is how a 10-second deploy turns into a 10-minute outage.

Update in small batches, commit each one, sleep briefly between batches. One big `UPDATE` runs in a single transaction that holds row locks and bloats the WAL:

```sql
DO $$
DECLARE
  batch_size int := 5000;
  done int;
BEGIN
  LOOP
    WITH cte AS (
      SELECT id FROM orders
      WHERE region IS NULL
      LIMIT batch_size FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED
    )
    UPDATE orders SET region = 'us-east'
    FROM cte WHERE orders.id = cte.id;
    GET DIAGNOSTICS done = ROW_COUNT;
    EXIT WHEN done = 0;
    PERFORM pg_sleep(0.1);
  END LOOP;
END $$;
```

`SKIP LOCKED` plus small batches keeps app traffic flowing.
